<article class=3D"ltx_document ltx_authors_1line ltx_leqno">
<h1 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_document">Leveraging Mixture of Experts (M=
oE) to Improve Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code</h1>
<div class=3D"ltx_dates">(2025)</div>

<div id=3D"abstract1" class=3D"ltx_abstract">
<h6 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_abstract">Abstract.</h6>
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Large language models for code have demonstrated strong =
performance across various software analytics tasks. However, their practic=
al deployment remains constrained by high computational costs, slow inferen=
ce speeds, substantial energy consumption, and an increased carbon footprin=
t. Knowledge distillation (KD) addresses these challenges by compressing la=
rge teacher models into smaller student models. Nevertheless, recent studie=
s indicate that student models distilled from a single teacher often exhibi=
t diminished adversarial robustness, even when robustness-aware distillatio=
n techniques are applied. These findings indicate a fundamental limitation =
of single-teacher distillation in transferring both high-quality and robust=
 knowledge. To address this limitation, we propose <span class=3D"ltx_text =
ltx_font_bold">Mixture of Experts Knowledge Distillation</span> (<span clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>) as a KD framework that leverag=
es a Mixture of Experts (MoE) architecture to facilitate more effective and=
 robust knowledge transfer from multiple specialized teachers to a compact =
student model. <span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> decomp=
oses the KD process into expert training, expert knowledge aggregation thro=
ugh a learned router, and student distillation from the aggregated expert k=
nowledge. We evaluate <span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>=
 on the vulnerability detection task using CodeBERT and GraphCodeBERT model=
s. Experimental results indicate that <span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_ital=
ic">MoEKD</span> enhances predictive performance by up to <span class=3D"lt=
x_text ltx_font_bold">13%</span> and adversarial robustness by up to <span =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">30%</span> relative to state-of-the-art KD=
 baselines, such as <span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</sp=
an> and <span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>. An ablation=
 study further demonstrates that aggregated expert knowledge enables traini=
ng ultra-compact student models to maintain competitive performance even wh=
en model size is reduced by approximately half. These findings underscore t=
he effectiveness of multi-expert knowledge aggregation in addressing key li=
mitations of current single-teacher distillation methods.</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_keywords">Language Models of Code, Model Compression, Kno=
wledge Distillation, Mixture of Experts (MoE), Robustness.
</div>
