<section id=3D"S1" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">1. </span>Introduction</h2>

<div id=3D"S1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Large language models for code have attra=
cted significant attention in the software engineering community for their =
ability to support a wide range of tasks, including clone detection <cite c=
lass=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Arshad<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bi=
b_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.=
bib175" title=3D"Codebert for code clone detection: a replication study" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>)</cite>, code summarization <cite class=3D"ltx_cit=
e ltx_citemacro_citep">(Ahmed<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.<=
/span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib375" title=3D=
"Automatic semantic augmentation of language model prompts (for code summar=
ization)" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>)</cite>, vulnerability detection <cite=
 class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Ding<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bi=
b_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.=
bib127" title=3D"Vulnerability detection with code language models: how far=
 are we?" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>)</cite>, and code search <cite class=
=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Chen<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal=
"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib128=
" title=3D"Code search is all you need? improving code suggestions with cod=
e search" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>)</cite>. Despite these advances, deplo=
ying these models on consumer-grade devices and in latency-sensitive applic=
ations remains challenging because of high computational costs, slow infere=
nce speeds, increased energy consumption, and a considerable carbon footpri=
nt <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Schwartz<span class=3D"ltx=
_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.=
13213v1#bib.bib74" title=3D"Green ai" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>)</cite>. T=
o address these challenges, researchers have investigated knowledge distill=
ation (KD) as a model compression technique that transfers knowledge from a=
 large teacher model to a smaller student model, thereby reducing model siz=
e, increasing inference speed, and mitigating environmental impact while la=
rgely preserving task performance <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cit=
ep">(Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib11" title=3D"Efficient and green l=
arge language models for software engineering: vision and the road ahead" c=
lass=3D"ltx_ref">2024b</a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#=
bib.bib9" title=3D"Greening large language models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref=
">a</a>; Liu<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib32" title=3D"PIONEER: improv=
ing the robustness of student models when compressing pre-trained models of=
 code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2026</a>; Panichella, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org=
/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib30" title=3D"Metamorphic-based many-objective dis=
tillation of llms for code-related tasks" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>; Chen<=
span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arx=
iv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib114" title=3D"Smaller but better: self-pace=
d knowledge distillation for lightweight yet effective lcms" class=3D"ltx_r=
ef">2025</a>)</cite>. However, Panichella et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite lt=
x_citemacro_citep">(Panichella, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.1321=
3v1#bib.bib30" title=3D"Metamorphic-based many-objective distillation of ll=
ms for code-related tasks" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite> empirically d=
emonstrated that knowledge-distilled student models often exhibit reduced r=
obustness and introduced <span id=3D"S1.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_=
italic">MORPH</span>, a KD-based approach that explicitly incorporates robu=
stness into the distillation process. Subsequent work by Abdul et al. <cite=
 class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Awal<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bi=
b_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.=
bib6" title=3D"A metamorphic testing perspective on knowledge distillation =
for language models of code: does the student deeply mimic the teacher?" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite> showed that, despite these improvements, s=
tudent models trained with MORPH remain less robust than their teacher coun=
terparts under adversarial attacks. These findings highlight a fundamental =
limitation of current knowledge distillation approaches that rely on a sing=
le teacher model to transfer knowledge to compact student models, a limitat=
ion that, to the best of our knowledge, has not been previously examined.</=
p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p2.2" class=3D"ltx_p">To better understand this limitation, it =
is important to examine knowledge transfer at the level of predictive confi=
dence rather than focusing solely on the final prediction. As illustrated i=
n Figure&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#S1.F1" title=
=3D"Figure 1 =E2=80=A3 1. Introduction =E2=80=A3 Leveraging Mixture of Expe=
rts (MoE) to Improve Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">1</span></a>, a teache=
r model and its distilled student assign the same vulnerability label to a =
code fragment under standard conditions; however, the teacher exhibits subs=
tantially higher confidence (<span id=3D"S1.p2.2.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_f=
ont_bold">0.99 vs. 0.51</span>), reflecting a more stable decision boundary=
. Under a minor adversarial perturbation (e.g., renaming identifiers: <span=
 id=3D"S1.p2.2.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">off</span> <math id=3D=
"S1.p2.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\rightarrow" display=3D"inline" =
intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92</mo><annota=
tion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\rightarrow</annotation></semantics></m=
ath> <span id=3D"S1.p2.2.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">addr</span> =
and
<span id=3D"S1.p2.2.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">sig</span> <math =
id=3D"S1.p2.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\rightarrow" display=3D"inl=
ine" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92</mo><a=
nnotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\rightarrow</annotation></semantic=
s></math> <span id=3D"S1.p2.2.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">tag</sp=
an>), the teacher=E2=80=99s confidence decreases but remains above the deci=
sion threshold, preserving the correct prediction, whereas the student=E2=
=80=99s confidence drops further, leading to misclassification. This exampl=
e suggests that knowledge transferred from a single teacher may be limited =
in scope and insufficient to adequately represent diverse or challenging de=
cision boundaries, especially those sensitive to adversarial perturbations,=
 underscoring the need for richer, more informative supervisory knowledge d=
uring distillation.</p>
</div>
