<figcaption class=3D"ltx_caption ltx_centering"><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_=
tag_figure">Figure 1. </span>A motivating example.</figcaption>
</figure>
<div id=3D"S1.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Motivated by this observation, we posit t=
hat more effective knowledge distillation can be achieved by aggregating co=
mplementary knowledge from multiple specialized teachers rather than relyin=
g on a single source. This perspective is analogous to higher education, wh=
ere students develop a comprehensive understanding of an entire curriculum =
by learning from multiple instructors, each specializing in a particular su=
bject area, rather than from a single generalist. Such specialization enabl=
es each teacher to provide deeper, more focused knowledge within their doma=
in, allowing students to develop a more comprehensive and robust understand=
ing. Extending this intuition to the knowledge distillation context, superv=
ision from multiple specialized expert models can provide richer and more d=
iverse knowledge than supervision from a single teacher. By aggregating kno=
wledge from these complementary experts, the student model is exposed to a =
broader spectrum of task-relevant information that may not be fully capture=
d by any single teacher. A <span id=3D"S1.p3.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_fon=
t_bold">Mixture of Experts</span> (MoE) <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemac=
ro_citep">(Jacobs<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib59" title=3D"Adaptive mix=
tures of local experts" class=3D"ltx_ref">1991</a>; Yuksel<span class=3D"lt=
x_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603=
.13213v1#bib.bib58" title=3D"Twenty years of mixture of experts" class=3D"l=
tx_ref">2012</a>)</cite> framework provides a principled abstraction for th=
is setting by enabling the systematic extraction and integration of expert =
knowledge during distillation. Building on this rationale, we propose <span=
 id=3D"S1.p3.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Mixture of Experts Knowl=
edge Distillation</span> (<span id=3D"S1.p3.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font=
_italic">MoEKD</span>), a distillation framework that leverages a Mixture o=
f Experts architecture to more effectively transfer knowledge from multiple=
 specialized teachers to a compact student model.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p">At a high level, <span id=3D"S1.p4.1.1" c=
lass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> decomposes the knowledge dis=
tillation process into three key components: <span id=3D"S1.p4.1.2" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">training phase</span>, <span id=3D"S1.p4.1.3"=
 class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">expert aggregation and logits fusion</s=
pan>, and <span id=3D"S1.p4.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">knowled=
ge distillation</span>. In the training phase, multiple expert models are t=
rained independently to specialize in distinct regions of the input space, =
and a router model is trained to select the most relevant experts for each =
input. During expert aggregation and logits fusion, a routing mechanism sel=
ectively combines the outputs of the top-<span id=3D"S1.p4.1.5" class=3D"lt=
x_text ltx_font_italic">k</span> relevant experts to generate unified super=
visory knowledge. This aggregated knowledge is subsequently transferred to =
a compact student model through a dedicated distillation process.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p5" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p5.1" class=3D"ltx_p">We empirically evaluate the effectiveness=
 of <span id=3D"S1.p5.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> =
in enhancing both predictive performance and adversarial robustness of comp=
ressed student models, using two code language models, CodeBERT and GraphCo=
deBERT, for the vulnerability detection task. Adversarial robustness is mea=
sured using three widely studied identifier renaming attacks: ALERT <cite c=
lass=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_=
etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bi=
b177" title=3D"Natural attack for pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_=
ref">2022</a>)</cite>, Metropolis Hastings Modifier (MHM) <cite class=3D"lt=
x_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Zhang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et=
 al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib176" tit=
le=3D"Generating adversarial examples for holding robustness of source code=
 processing models" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>)</cite>, and WIR-Random <cit=
e class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Zeng<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_b=
ib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib=
.bib378" title=3D"An extensive study on pre-trained models for program unde=
rstanding and generation" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>)</cite>. The experimen=
tal results indicate that <span id=3D"S1.p5.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font=
_italic">MoEKD</span> increases the predictive performance of student model=
s by up to <span id=3D"S1.p5.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">13%</spa=
n> compared to state-of-the-art baselines, including <span id=3D"S1.p5.1.4"=
 class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> and <span id=3D"S1.p5=
.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>. Regarding adversari=
al robustness, <span id=3D"S1.p5.1.6" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Mo=
EKD</span> achieves improvements of up to <span id=3D"S1.p5.1.7" class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_font_bold">30%</span> over these baselines. Furthermore, an abl=
ation study demonstrates that the high-quality knowledge aggregated from mu=
ltiple expert models enables the training of ultra-compact student models t=
hat maintain competitive performance while reducing model size by approxima=
tely half compared to the baseline models. We summarize the contribution of=
 this paper as follows:</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p6" class=3D"ltx_para">
<ul id=3D"S1.I1" class=3D"ltx_itemize">
<li id=3D"S1.I1.i1" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S1.I1.i1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.I1.i1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S1.I1.i1.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Novelty:</span> To the best of our knowledge, t=
his study is the first to adapt the Mixture of Experts (MoE) framework in t=
he context of knowledge distillation.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S1.I1.i2" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S1.I1.i2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.I1.i2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S1.I1.i2.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Technique:</span> We propose and implement <spa=
n id=3D"S1.I1.i2.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>, a=
 knowledge distillation framework that leverages a Mixture of Experts parad=
igm to aggregate knowledge from multiple specialized expert models and tran=
sfer this aggregated knowledge to a compact student model, thereby improvin=
g both predictive performance and adversarial robustness of compressed stud=
ent models.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S1.I1.i3" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S1.I1.i3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.I1.i3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S1.I1.i3.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Evaluation: </span>We conduct a thorough empiri=
cal evaluation to demonstrate the effectiveness of <span id=3D"S1.I1.i3.p1.=
1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> in improving both pred=
ictive performance and adversarial robustness of compressed student models =
compared to state-of-the-art KD baselines.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S1.I1.i4" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S1.I1.i4.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.I1.i4.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S1.I1.i4.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Open science:</span> we have open-sourced our r=
eplication package to facilitate future research<span id=3D"footnote1" clas=
s=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">1</sup><span =
class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=3D"ltx=
_note_mark">1</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">1</span><a href=3D"=
https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.16127320" title=3D"" class=3D"ltx_ref ltx_ur=
l ltx_font_typewriter">https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.16127320</a></span></=
span></span>.</p>
</div>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S2" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">2. </span>Preliminaries</h2>

<section id=3D"S2.SS1" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">2.1. </span>Mixture of Experts (=
MoE)</h3>

<div id=3D"S2.SS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The Mixture of Experts framework is a=
 collaborative learning approach that integrates multiple specialized model=
s, known as experts, each dedicated to distinct regions of the input space =
<cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Yuksel<span class=3D"ltx_text=
 ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213=
v1#bib.bib58" title=3D"Twenty years of mixture of experts" class=3D"ltx_ref=
">2012</a>)</cite>. First introduced by Jacobs et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_ci=
te ltx_citemacro_citep">(Jacobs<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al=
.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib59" title=
=3D"Adaptive mixtures of local experts" class=3D"ltx_ref">1991</a>)</cite> =
in 1991, this methodology partitions the input space into subspaces, trains=
 individual experts within each partition, and aggregates their outputs via=
 a routing mechanism, typically a gating function. The principal concept un=
derlying MoE is the dynamic selection and activation of the most suitable e=
xperts for each input instance. Generally, a MoE architecture consists of t=
hree primary components:</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S2.SS1.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<ul id=3D"S2.I1" class=3D"ltx_itemize">
<li id=3D"S2.I1.i1" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S2.I1.i1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.I1.i1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S2.I1.i1.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Experts: </span> A set of specialized models, e=
ach trained to identify patterns within distinct regions of the input space=
 or to address specific subtasks. While experts may share the same architec=
ture, they learn different representations. Experts may be implemented as i=
ndependent neural networks or as specialized sub-models that acquire comple=
mentary representations across various regions of the input space.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S2.I1.i2" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S2.I1.i2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.I1.i2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S2.I1.i2.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Gating Network (Router): </span> A routing mech=
anism that assigns each input to one or more experts by generating a set of=
 weights or probabilities, which determine expert activation and their resp=
ective contributions to the final prediction. This router is typically impl=
emented as a lightweight gating network that manages expert selection and c=
ontribution for each input instance.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S2.I1.i3" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S2.I1.i3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.I1.i3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S2.I1.i3.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Aggregation Mechanism (Combiner): </span> A com=
ponent that integrates the outputs of the selected experts, typically using=
 a weighted sum determined by the gating network=E2=80=99s outputs, to gene=
rate the final model prediction.</p>
</div>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id=3D"S2.SS1.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS1.p3.6" class=3D"ltx_p">Let <math id=3D"S2.SS1.p3.1.m1" class=
