with the expert parameters <math id=3D"S2.SS1.p5.6.m6" class=3D"ltx_Math" a=
lttext=3D"\Theta_{x}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><ms=
ub><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=98</mi><mi>x</mi></msub><annotation encod=
ing=3D"application/x-tex">\Theta_{x}</annotation></semantics></math> or sel=
ectively optimizing a subset of these parameters depending on the deploymen=
t setting.</p>
</div>
<figure id=3D"S2.F2" class=3D"ltx_figure"><img src=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2603.13213v1/x2.png" id=3D"S2.F2.g1" class=3D"ltx_graphics ltx_centering =
ltx_img_landscape" width=3D"326" height=3D"259" alt=3D"Refer to caption">
<figcaption class=3D"ltx_caption ltx_centering"><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_=
tag_figure">Figure 2. </span>An Illustrative Architecture of a Mixture of E=
xperts Framework.</figcaption>
</figure>
<div id=3D"S2.SS1.p6" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS1.p6.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Figure <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/h=
tml/2603.13213v1#S2.F2" title=3D"Figure 2 =E2=80=A3 2.1. Mixture of Experts=
 (MoE) =E2=80=A3 2. Preliminaries =E2=80=A3 Leveraging Mixture of Experts (=
MoE) to Improve Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code" class=
=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">2</span></a> presents a r=
epresentative MoE architecture. Upon receiving an input, the routing module=
 assesses the relevance of each expert and activates a subset for processin=
g. In this scenario, the first and third experts are selected. The outputs =
from the selected experts are subsequently combined by the aggregation modu=
le to produce the final output.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S2.SS2" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">2.2. </span>Knowledge Distillati=
on</h3>

<div id=3D"S2.SS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The deployment of language models for=
 code is frequently constrained by high computational costs, significant me=
mory demands, and environmental impacts, including carbon emissions <cite c=
lass=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Schwartz<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_=
bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bi=
b.bib74" title=3D"Green ai" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>; Xu and McAuley, <a =
href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib66" title=3D"A survey on=
 model compression and acceleration for pretrained language models" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>)</cite>. To mitigate these limitations and promote su=
stainable deployment, model compression methods, such as knowledge distilla=
tion (KD) <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Hinton<span class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2603.13213v1#bib.bib42" title=3D"Distilling the knowledge in a neural net=
work" class=3D"ltx_ref">2015</a>)</cite>, have been widely adopted to reduc=
e resource usage while maintaining model performance. Knowledge distillatio=
n involves transferring knowledge from a large, expressive teacher model to=
 a smaller, more efficient student model. Rather than relying exclusively o=
n hard labels, the student is trained with soft supervision representations=
, such as probability distributions or teacher-provided logits, often using=
 unlabeled data. This approach enables the student to approximate the teach=
er=E2=80=99s functional behavior and decision boundaries, thereby preservin=
g much of the teacher=E2=80=99s generalization ability while significantly =
reducing model size and computational requirements.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S2.SS2.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS2.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Knowledge distillation methods can be=
 categorized as either task-specific or task-agnostic, depending on how com=
pressed models are applied <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Xu=
<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://ar=
xiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib65" title=3D"A survey on knowledge distill=
ation of large language models" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>)</cite>. Task-sp=
ecific distillation compresses a teacher model that has already been fine-t=
uned for a downstream task, allowing the student model to be directly deplo=
yed for the same task. In contrast, task-agnostic distillation compresses a=
 pre-trained model prior to downstream adaptation, a process that typically=
 requires expensive, large-scale training. Given the substantially higher c=
omputational and time costs associated with task-agnostic approaches, this =
study focuses on task-specific distillation, which provides a more practica=
l and resource-efficient solution for software analytics tasks <cite class=
=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"=
> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib7" t=
itle=3D"Compressing pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_ref"=
>2023</a>)</cite>.</p>
</div>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"S3" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">3. </span>Methodology</h2>

<section id=3D"S3.SS1" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">3.1. </span>Problem Formulation<=
/h3>

<div id=3D"S3.SS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Standard knowledge distillation typic=
ally relies on a single teacher model to supervise the training of a compac=
t student model. While this approach effectively transfers average task beh=
avior, it may be limited if the teacher does not adequately represent diver=
se or challenging decision regions, especially those sensitive to adversari=
al perturbations. For example, complex software engineering tasks such as v=
ulnerability detection encompass a wide range of patterns, behaviors, and s=
emantic cues that are unlikely to be uniformly captured by a single model <=
cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text lt=
x_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#=
bib.bib54" title=3D"One-for-all does not work! enhancing vulnerability dete=
ction by mixture-of-experts (moe)" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite>. In t=
hese complex learning scenarios, robust understanding often emerges from ex=
posure to multiple perspectives rather than instruction from a single sourc=
e. This situation is analogous to higher education, where students do not d=
epend on a single instructor to master an entire curriculum. Instead, learn=
ing is distributed among multiple teachers, each specializing in a specific=
 subject area such as physics, mathematics, or chemistry. Such specializati=
on enables each teacher to provide deeper, more focused knowledge within th=
eir domain, allowing students to develop a more comprehensive and robust un=
derstanding.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Extending this analogy, knowledge dis=
tillation can similarly benefit from supervision by multiple expert models =
(teachers) rather than a single teacher. In this context, each expert may s=
pecialize in capturing distinct aspects of the task, such as particular vul=
nerability categories, recurring code patterns, semantic structures, or fea=
tures relevant to adversarial robustness. Aggregating information from thes=
e specialized experts exposes the student model to a broader, more diverse =
set of learning features that may not be fully represented by a single teac=
her. A <span id=3D"S3.SS1.p2.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">mixture =
of experts</span> framework provides a principled abstraction for this sett=
ing by enabling the systematic extraction and integration of expert knowled=
ge during distillation. We hypothesize that distilling knowledge from multi=
ple specialized experts can improve task performance and enhance adversaria=
l robustness compared with single-teacher distillation.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.p3.7" class=3D"ltx_p">Building on the multi-expert learning=
 paradigm, the knowledge distillation setting for this study is formalized =
as follows. Let <math id=3D"S3.SS1.p3.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\=
mathcal{D}=3D\{(x_{i},y_{i})\}_{i=3D1}^{N}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":l=
iteral"><semantics><mrow><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=
=9F</mi><mo>=3D</mo><msubsup><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">{</mo><mrow><mo s=
tretchy=3D"false">(</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><m=
i>y</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow><mo stretchy=
=3D"false">}</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>N<=
/mi></msubsup></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{D}=
=3D\{(x_{i},y_{i})\}_{i=3D1}^{N}</annotation></semantics></math> represent =
a labeled dataset for a software engineering task, where <math id=3D"S3.SS1=
.p3.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"x_{i}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D=
":literal"><semantics><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-tex">x_{i}</annotation></semantics></math> denotes a code=
 fragment and <math id=3D"S3.SS1.p3.3.m3" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"y_{=
i}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>i=
</mi></msub><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">y_{i}</annotation></=
semantics></math> its corresponding label. Consider a set of expert models =
<math id=3D"S3.SS1.p3.4.m4" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\{T_{1},\ldots,T_=
{K}\}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=
=3D"false">{</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=
=3D"normal">=E2=80=A6</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>K</mi></msub><mo st=
retchy=3D"false">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\{=
T_{1},\ldots,T_{K}\}</annotation></semantics></math>, each specializing in =
distinct aspects of the task, and a compact student model <math id=3D"S3.SS=
1.p3.5.m5" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"S" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":l=
iteral"><semantics><mi>S</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">S</=
annotation></semantics></math>. The goal of KD is to train <math id=3D"S3.S=
S1.p3.6.m6" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"S" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":=
literal"><semantics><mi>S</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">S<=
/annotation></semantics></math> to effectively utilize the knowledge impart=
ed by the expert models. Unlike conventional approaches that rely on a sing=
le teacher, this study investigates a Mixture of Experts scenario in which =
the student receives an aggregated supervisory representation, <math id=3D"=
S3.SS1.p3.7.m7" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\mathcal{A}(T_{1},\ldots,T_{K=
})" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi class=3D"lt=
x_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9C</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=
=E2=80=8B</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn>=
</msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=80=A6</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><=
mi>T</mi><mi>K</mi></msub><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annot=
ation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{A}(T_{1},\ldots,T_{K})</annot=
ation></semantics></math>. Accordingly, the problem addressed in this study=
 is to determine whether distilling knowledge from a mixture of specialized=
 experts improves the predictive performance and robustness of the student =
model relative to single teacher distillation under both standard and adver=
sarial evaluation settings.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To address this problem, we propose <=
span id=3D"S3.SS1.p4.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>, =
a knowledge distillation framework that integrates a Mixture of Experts (Mo=
E) mechanism to systematically extract and aggregate knowledge from multipl=
e specialized expert (teacher) models. The subsequent section outlines the =
proposed framework, including the construction of expert models, the aggreg=
ation of expert outputs, and the training procedure for transferring the ag=
gregated knowledge to the student model.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S3.SS2" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">3.2. </span>Approach: <span id=
=3D"S3.SS2.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> Framework</=
h3>

<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The proposed <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p1.1.=
1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> framework leverages a Mi=
xture of Experts paradigm to extract specialized knowledge from multiple ex=
pert (teacher) models for knowledge distillation. Figure <a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#S3.F3" title=3D"Figure 3 =E2=80=A3 3.2. Approa=
ch: MoEKD Framework =E2=80=A3 3. Methodology =E2=80=A3 Leveraging Mixture o=
f Experts (MoE) to Improve Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Co=
de" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">3</span></a> ill=
ustrates the overall <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_=
italic">MoEKD</span> pipeline. The framework consists of three sequential p=
hases: (i) expert and router training, where multiple specialized experts a=
re learned from partitioned input spaces and a router is trained to estimat=
e expert relevance; (ii) output aggregation and logit-level fusion, where t=
he router dynamically selects the top-<math id=3D"S3.SS2.p1.1.m1" class=3D"=
ltx_Math" alttext=3D"k" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><=
mi>k</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">k</annotation></semanti=
cs></math> experts and combines their outputs into a unified representation=
; and (iii) knowledge distillation, where the aggregated expert knowledge i=
s transferred to a compact student model using KL divergence-based supervis=
ion without hard labels. The following subsections describe the design of e=
ach component of the <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_=
italic">MoEKD</span> framework, using the BigVul <cite class=3D"ltx_cite lt=
x_citemacro_citep">(Fan<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>=
, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib52" title=3D"AC/c++=
 code vulnerability dataset with code changes and cve summaries" class=3D"l=
tx_ref">2020</a>)</cite> vulnerability detection dataset as an illustrative=
 example.</p>
</div>
<figure id=3D"S3.F3" class=3D"ltx_figure"><img src=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2603.13213v1/x3.png" id=3D"S3.F3.g1" class=3D"ltx_graphics ltx_centering =
ltx_img_landscape" width=3D"654" height=3D"354" alt=3D"Refer to caption">
<figcaption class=3D"ltx_caption ltx_centering"><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_=
tag_figure">Figure 3. </span>Overview of the proposed <span id=3D"S3.F3.2.1=
" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> framework, which trains m=
ultiple specialized experts and a router, aggregates selected expert output=
s at the logit level, and distills the fused knowledge into a compact stude=
nt model.</figcaption>
</figure>
<section id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">3.2.1. </span>Training Phase<=
/h4>

<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The training phase of <span id=
=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> con=
sists of three key steps: partitioning the input space, training specialize=
d expert models, and training the router to estimate expert relevance. Foll=
owing the study Yang et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Y=
ang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib54" title=3D"One-for-all does not work!=
 enhancing vulnerability detection by mixture-of-experts (moe)" class=3D"lt=
x_ref">2025</a>)</cite>, we train the expert and router model separately to=
 ease the training complexity.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p2.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Input space partitioning via CWE taxonomy:=
 </span>An important design consideration in the Mixture of Experts framewo=
rk is the partitioning of the input space among experts, since effective sp=
ecialization depends on a meaningful division of inputs. The goal is to ass=
ign each expert a subset of inputs with coherent, recurring patterns, allow=
ing them to capture task-specific nuances more effectively than a generalis=
t model. In vulnerability detection, this strategy aligns with categorizati=
on schemes that group common software system weaknesses, such as buffer ove=
rflows, improper authentication, and information leakage, based on shared c=
haracteristics. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Christey<span=
 class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.o=
rg/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib53" title=3D"Common weakness enumeration" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2013</a>)</cite>.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The Common Weakness Enumeration =
(CWE) taxonomy guides input space partitioning because distinct vulnerabili=
ty categories exhibit unique code patterns and semantic properties that nec=
essitate specialized modeling. Nevertheless, assigning an expert to each CW=
E type is impractical given the large number of categories, as demonstrated=
 by the BigVul dataset <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Fan<sp=
an class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv=
.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib52" title=3D"AC/c++ code vulnerability datase=
t with code changes and cve summaries" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>)</cite>, =
which includes 88 CWE types and exhibits a highly imbalanced instance distr=
ibution. The limited representation of many CWE categories further complica=
tes the development of reliable experts and increases training overhead. Co=
nsequently, following the methodology outlined by Yang et al. <cite class=
=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal=
"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib54"=
 title=3D"One-for-all does not work! enhancing vulnerability detection by m=
ixture-of-experts (moe)" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite>, the hierarchic=
al structure of the CWE taxonomy is employed, and input splitting is perfor=
med at a coarse level by selecting top-level CWE categories. This method cl=
usters related vulnerabilities with similar characteristics, enabling each =
expert to generalize across semantically related subcategories. CWE categor=
ies with insufficient training instances are consolidated into a single gro=
up to ensure stable expert training and to control model complexity. Furthe=
rmore, consistent with established knowledge distillation protocols, the tr=
aining data is divided into two separate subsets: one for training the teac=
her model and the other for extracting soft knowledge to guide student trai=
ning. To ensure reliable router learning in this context, each CWE group is=
 assigned at least 100 training samples, following the recommendation of Ya=
ng et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Anonymous, <a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib399" title=3D"Replication pa=
ckage, model compression vs. adversarial robustness: an empirical study on =
pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite>. Accordingly=
, 10 input subspaces are constructed, each corresponding to a specific CWE =
category: <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_typewr=
iter">CWE-66</span>, <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_=
font_typewriter">CWE-707</span>, <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3.1.3" class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_font_typewriter">CWE-399</span>, <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3.1.4=
" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter">CWE-264</span>, <span id=3D"S3.SS2=
.SSS1.p3.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter">CWE-284</span>, <span =
id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3.1.6" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter">CWE-682</s=
pan>, <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3.1.7" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter=
">CWE-691</span>, <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3.1.8" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_fon=
t_typewriter">CWE-189</span>, <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p3.1.9" class=3D"ltx_=
text ltx_font_typewriter">CWE-unknown</span>, and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p=
3.1.10" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter">CWE-other</span>. An expert =
model is trained for each subspace, specializing in a particular vulnerabil=
ity. This approach yields a manageable number of experts and establishes a =
principled basis for extracting expert knowledge that is subsequently trans=
ferred to the student model via knowledge distillation.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p4.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Expert training: </span>Each expert model =
is trained to specialize in a specific vulnerability subspace, aiming to ex=
tract focused and discriminative knowledge for subsequent transfer to the s=
tudent model via knowledge distillation. For a given vulnerability category=
, the expert is optimized to distinguish code instances associated with tha=
t category from all other code, thereby enabling the model to learn categor=
y-specific patterns and decision boundaries. During training, code samples =
from the target vulnerability category are labeled as positive instances, w=
hereas all other samples, including those from other categories and non-vul=
nerable code, are labeled as negative instances. This approach encourages e=
ach expert to capture fine-grained characteristics relevant to its assigned=
 subspace.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p5" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p5.5" class=3D"ltx_p">For each vulnerability category =
<math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p5.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\mathrm{CWE}=
_{i}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msub><mi>CWE</mi><=
mi>i</mi></msub><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathrm{CWE}_{i}=
</annotation></semantics></math>, a dedicated expert model is trained to es=
timate the probability that a code fragment <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p5.2.m2=
" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"c" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><=
semantics><mi>c</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">c</annotatio=
n></semantics></math> is vulnerable. Each expert is instantiated by fine-tu=
ning a pre-trained code language model, such as CodeBERT, and is augmented =
with a binary classification head tailored to its assigned vulnerability su=
bspace. The expert generates a prediction <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p5.3.m3" =
class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"P(\mathrm{vul}\mid c,\mathrm{CWE}_{i},\theta_=
{e}^{i})" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi=
><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"fals=
e">(</mo><mrow><mi>vul</mi><mo>=E2=88=A3</mo><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>,</mo><msu=
b><mi>CWE</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msubsup><mi>=CE=B8</mi><mi>e</mi>=
<mi>i</mi></msubsup></mrow></mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow></mro=
w><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">P(\mathrm{vul}\mid c,\mathrm{C=
WE}_{i},\theta_{e}^{i})</annotation></semantics></math>, where <math id=3D"=
S3.SS2.SSS1.p5.4.m4" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\theta_{e}^{i}" display=
=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msubsup><mi>=CE=B8</mi><mi>e</m=
i><mi>i</mi></msubsup><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\theta_{e}=
^{i}</annotation></semantics></math> represents the parameters of the <math=
 id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p5.5.m5" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"i" display=3D"inl=
ine" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>i</mi><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">i</annotation></semantics></math>-th expert. Training is cond=
ucted on a category-specific dataset by minimizing a binary cross-entropy l=
oss defined over vulnerable and non-vulnerable instances. This approach ena=
bles each expert to learn discriminative representations specific to its ta=
rget vulnerability type.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p6" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p6.7" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p6.7.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Router training: </span> The router is tra=
ined to identify which expert models are most relevant for a given input, e=
nabling effective extraction of expert knowledge during distillation. Its r=
ole is to capture distinguishing characteristics of Common Weakness Enumera=
tion (CWE) categories, ensuring that the student model receives guidance fr=
om the most suitable experts. Router training is therefore formulated as a =
multi-class classification task over CWE categories, with the goal of predi=
cting the probability that an input code fragment belongs to each CWE-speci=
fic subspace. Given an input code fragment <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p6.1.m1"=
 class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"c" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><s=
emantics><mi>c</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">c</annotation=
></semantics></math>, the objective is to assign it to one of the CWE categ=
ories <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p6.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\mathr=
m{CWE}_{i}\in\{\mathrm{CWE}_{1},\mathrm{CWE}_{2},\ldots,\mathrm{CWE}_{N}\}"=
 display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>CWE</mi>=
<mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=E2=88=88</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">{</mo><msub=
><mi>CWE</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>CWE</mi><mn>2</mn></msub>=
<mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=80=A6</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>CWE<=
/mi><mi>N</mi></msub><mo stretchy=3D"false">}</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation=
 encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathrm{CWE}_{i}\in\{\mathrm{CWE}_{1},\math=
rm{CWE}_{2},\ldots,\mathrm{CWE}_{N}\}</annotation></semantics></math>, wher=
e <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p6.3.m3" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"N" display=
=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>N</mi><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-tex">N</annotation></semantics></math> denotes the total =
number of CWE type sand corresponds to the number of experts. To this end, =
the routing model is trained to estimate the probability that <math id=3D"S=
3.SS2.SSS1.p6.4.m4" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"c" display=3D"inline" int=
ent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>c</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x=
-tex">c</annotation></semantics></math> belongs to a specific CWE category =
<math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p6.5.m5" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\mathrm{CWE}=
_{i}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msub><mi>CWE</mi><=
mi>i</mi></msub><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathrm{CWE}_{i}=
</annotation></semantics></math>, denoted as <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p6.6.m=
6" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"g_{i}(\mathrm{CWE}_{i}\mid c,\theta_{g})" =
display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>g</mi><mi=
>i</mi></msub><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mrow><mo str=
etchy=3D"false">(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>CWE</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=E2=88=
=A3</mo><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>=CE=B8</mi><mi>g</mi></msub></m=
row></mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-tex">g_{i}(\mathrm{CWE}_{i}\mid c,\theta_{g})</annotation=
></semantics></math>, where <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p6.7.m7" class=3D"ltx_M=
ath" alttext=3D"\theta_{g}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semanti=
cs><msub><mi>=CE=B8</mi><mi>g</mi></msub><annotation encoding=3D"applicatio=
n/x-tex">\theta_{g}</annotation></semantics></math> represents the paramete=
rs of the router.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p7" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p7.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Similar to the expert models, th=
e router is built on a pre-trained code language model (e.g., CodeBERT) tha=
t serves as the backbone and is augmented with a multi-class classification=
 head to predict CWE categories. The distribution of CWE types is highly im=
balanced and exhibits a pronounced long tail, a characteristic commonly obs=
erved in vulnerability datasets <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep=
">(Zhou<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib55" title=3D"The devil is in the ta=
ils: how long-tailed code distributions impact large language models" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>)</cite>. To address this imbalance during router trai=
ning, the focal loss function <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">=
(Lin<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https:=
//arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib56" title=3D"Focal loss for dense obje=
ct detection" class=3D"ltx_ref">2017</a>)</cite> is employed, as recommende=
d by Yang et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Yang<span cl=
ass=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/=
html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib54" title=3D"One-for-all does not work! enhancing =
vulnerability detection by mixture-of-experts (moe)" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025=
</a>)</cite>, instead of the standard cross-entropy loss. The focal loss pr=
ioritizes hard-to-classify examples and reduces the influence of dominant c=
lasses, thereby improving the router=E2=80=99s capacity to accurately model=
 rare CWE categories. The overall focal loss for the router model over the =
training dataset <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p7.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttex=
t=3D"\mathcal{D}_{R}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><ms=
ub><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9F</mi><mi>R</mi></msub=
><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{D}_{R}</annotation></s=
emantics></math> is defined as:</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS1.p8" class=3D"ltx_para">
<table id=3D"S3.E2" class=3D"ltx_equation ltx_eqn_table">

