<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS2.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS2.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Aggregation at the logit level p=
reserves the relative confidence structure learned by each expert and avoid=
s distortions associated with premature probability normalization. The resu=
lting fused logits, <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS2.p4.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alt=
text=3D"\boldsymbol{\ell}_{i}^{\text{MoE}}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":l=
iteral"><semantics><msubsup><mi class=3D"ltx_mathvariant_bold" mathvariant=
=3D"bold">=E2=84=93</mi><mi>i</mi><mtext>MoE</mtext></msubsup><annotation e=
ncoding=3D"application/x-tex">\boldsymbol{\ell}_{i}^{\text{MoE}}</annotatio=
n></semantics></math>, serve as the final supervisory representation used f=
or downstream evaluation and knowledge distillation.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS2.p5" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS2.p5.1" class=3D"ltx_p">It is important to note that the=
 router is trained exclusively on vulnerable code and, consequently, does n=
ot explicitly learn routing behavior for non-vulnerable inputs. This situat=
ion raises questions about how non-vulnerable samples are handled during lo=
git fusion. In <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS2.p5.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_i=
talic">MoEKD</span>, non-vulnerable inputs are routed according to their si=
milarity to vulnerable code patterns, and each expert is trained on both a =
specific CWE vulnerability and non-vulnerable code, which enables reliable =
processing of non-vulnerable inputs. Consequently, even if non-vulnerable c=
ode is routed to different experts, this does not pose a limitation, as all=
 experts have the capability to handle non-vulnerable instances by design <=
cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text lt=
x_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#=
bib.bib54" title=3D"One-for-all does not work! enhancing vulnerability dete=
ction by mixture-of-experts (moe)" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite>.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">3.2.3. </span>Knowledge Disti=
llation</h4>

<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">This section outlines the knowle=
dge distillation process in <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_te=
xt ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>, including the selection of compact studen=
t architectures and the distillation objective for transferring aggregated =
expert knowledge to the student model.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p2.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Student model architecture: </span>The stu=
dent models in the proposed <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p2.1.2" class=3D"ltx_te=
xt ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> framework reuse compact architectures deri=
ved from existing model compression techniques rather than introducing new =
architectural designs. The selection of student architectures is guided by =
two key constraints: <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p2.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_=
font_italic">deployment feasibility</span> and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p2.1=
.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">experimental control</span>. First, =
we target compact models suitable for integration into integrated developme=
nt environments and therefore impose a strict model size constraint of appr=
oximately 3 MB. This choice builds on prior work on deployable vulnerabilit=
y-detection models and aligns with practical usage scenarios in software de=
velopment workflows <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Svyatkovs=
kiy<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib57" title=3D"Fast and memory-efficient =
neural code completion" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021</a>; Shi<span class=3D"ltx_t=
ext ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13=
213v1#bib.bib7" title=3D"Compressing pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" =
class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>)</cite>. Second, robustness-aware objectives are=
 intentionally excluded from the original multi-objective compression proce=
ss during the identification of candidate student architectures. This strat=
egy isolates the effect of Mixture of Experts supervision and enables asses=
sment of whether improvements in predictive performance and adversarial rob=
ustness can be achieved through expert knowledge distillation alone, withou=
t reliance on robustness-oriented architectural optimization.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Under these constraints, we sele=
ct student architectures generated by <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p3.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3=
.p3.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>, two established =
compression frameworks that produce reduced capacity variants of large pret=
rained code language models via structured compression strategies. Among th=
e Pareto-optimal configurations produced by these methods, we select those =
that satisfy the imposed size constraint while maintaining sufficient model=
 capacity. The selected architectures remain fixed throughout training, ens=
uring that any observed performance or robustness gains can be attributed t=
o the proposed <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p3.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_i=
talic">MoEKD</span> framework rather than differences in model structure.</=
p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p4.2" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p4.2.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Student training objective: </span> The st=
udent training stage in <span id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p4.2.2" class=3D"ltx_text l=
tx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> aims to facilitate effective learning in a com=
pact student model by leveraging aggregated knowledge from multiple special=
ized experts. For each input code fragment <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p4.1.m1"=
 class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"x_{i}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal=
"><semantics><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">x_{i}</annotation></semantics></math>, the expert aggregation=
 module generates fused logits <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p4.2.m2" class=3D"lt=
x_Math" alttext=3D"\boldsymbol{\ell}_{i}^{\text{MoE}}" display=3D"inline" i=
ntent=3D":literal"><semantics><msubsup><mi class=3D"ltx_mathvariant_bold" m=
athvariant=3D"bold">=E2=84=93</mi><mi>i</mi><mtext>MoE</mtext></msubsup><an=
notation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\boldsymbol{\ell}_{i}^{\text{MoE}}<=
/annotation></semantics></math>, which represent complementary information =
from the most relevant experts as determined by the router. These fused log=
its provide soft supervision to guide the student model during knowledge di=
stillation.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p5" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p5.2" class=3D"ltx_p">Let <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p5.1=
.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\boldsymbol{\ell}_{i}^{S}" display=3D"in=
line" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msubsup><mi class=3D"ltx_mathvariant_=
bold" mathvariant=3D"bold">=E2=84=93</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>S</mi></msubsup><ann=
otation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\boldsymbol{\ell}_{i}^{S}</annotatio=
n></semantics></math> denote the output logits produced by the student mode=
l for input <math id=3D"S3.SS2.SSS3.p5.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"=
x_{i}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msub><mi>x</mi><m=
i>i</mi></msub><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">x_{i}</annotation=
></semantics></math>. Rather than combining hard-label supervision with dis=
tillation, we formulate student training exclusively as a knowledge distill=
ation problem, in which the objective is to align the student=E2=80=99s pre=
dictive distribution with that of the aggregated experts. This design choic=
e enables the student model to capture fine-grained decision boundaries and=
 inter-class relationships learned by the expert ensemble, without being co=
nstrained by hard labels. Formally, the student model is trained by minimiz=
ing the Kullback-Leibler divergence between the softened output distributio=
