<section id=3D"S4" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">4. </span>Empirical Evaluation</h2>

<div id=3D"S4.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Following the description of the proposed=
 <span id=3D"S4.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> fra=
mework and its components, we present an empirical evaluation to assess its=
 effectiveness in terms of predictive performance and robustness compared w=
ith state-of-the-art knowledge distillation approaches. This evaluation add=
resses the following research questions:</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S4.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<ul id=3D"S4.I1" class=3D"ltx_itemize">
<li id=3D"S4.I1.i1" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S4.I1.i1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.I1.i1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S4.I1.i1.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">RQ1</span>: <span id=3D"S4.I1.i1.p1.1.2" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Does knowledge distillation from a mixture of=
 specialized experts enhance the performance of the student model relative =
to single-teacher distillation?</span></p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S4.I1.i2" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S4.I1.i2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.I1.i2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S4.I1.i2.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">RQ2</span>: <span id=3D"S4.I1.i2.p1.1.2" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Does a mixture of experts-based knowledge dis=
tillation improve the adversarial robustness of the student model relative =
to single-teacher distillation?</span></p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S4.I1.i3" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S4.I1.i3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.I1.i3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S4.I1.i3.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">RQ3</span>: <span id=3D"S4.I1.i3.p1.1.2" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">RQ3: Does MoEKD retain its performance advant=
ages over single-teacher distillation under more aggressive student model c=
ompression?</span></p>
</div>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<section id=3D"S4.SS1" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">4.1. </span>Knowledge Distillati=
on Baselines</h3>

<div id=3D"S4.SS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Several knowledge distillation approa=
ches have been proposed for language models of code, including <span id=3D"=
S4.SS1.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> <cite c=
lass=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_e=
tal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib=
7" title=3D"Compressing pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_=
ref">2023</a>)</cite>, <span id=3D"S4.SS1.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_fon=
t_italic">AVATAR</span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Shi<s=
pan class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxi=
v.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib9" title=3D"Greening large language models o=
f code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024a</a>)</cite>, <span id=3D"S4.SS1.p1.1.3" cla=
ss=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_ci=
temacro_citep">(Panichella, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#=
bib.bib30" title=3D"Metamorphic-based many-objective distillation of llms f=
or code-related tasks" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite>, <span id=3D"S4.S=
S1.p1.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">PIONEER</span> <cite class=3D=
"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Liu<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> e=
t al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib32" tit=
le=3D"PIONEER: improving the robustness of student models when compressing =
pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2026</a>)</cite>, and <span i=
d=3D"S4.SS1.p1.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">SODA</span> <cite cl=
ass=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Chen<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_e=
tal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib=
114" title=3D"Smaller but better: self-paced knowledge distillation for lig=
htweight yet effective lcms" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite>. In this st=
udy, we restrict our baselines to methods that produce compact student mode=
ls of size comparable to 3 MB. Except for <span id=3D"S4.SS1.p1.1.6" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">SODA</span>, all of these approaches generate=
 student models of approximately 3 MB in size. Both <span id=3D"S4.SS1.p1.1=
.7" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> and <span id=3D"S4.SS1.=
p1.1.8" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">PIONEER</span> explicitly incorp=
orate robustness-oriented objectives during knowledge distillation. As our =
study intentionally excludes robustness-aware optimization to isolate the e=
ffect of Mixture of Experts supervision, these methods are not considered a=
s baselines. Based on these criteria, we select <span id=3D"S4.SS1.p1.1.9" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> and <span id=3D"S4.SS1=
.p1.1.10" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> as baseline appr=
oaches for comparison.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S4.SS2" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">4.2. </span>Datasets and Subject=
s</h3>

<div id=3D"S4.SS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To ensure a fair assessment of the pe=
rformance and robustness improvements introduced by the mixture of expert-b=
ased knowledge distillation, we use the same models and tasks as those used=
 by the baseline knowledge distillation=E2=80=93based approaches described =
in Section <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#S4.SS1" title=3D"=
4.1. Knowledge Distillation Baselines =E2=80=A3 4. Empirical Evaluation =E2=
=80=A3 Leveraging Mixture of Experts (MoE) to Improve Knowledge Distillatio=
n for Language Models of Code" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text lt=
x_ref_tag">4.1</span></a>. For the vulnerability detection task, the BigVul=
 dataset <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Fan<span class=3D"lt=
x_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603=
.13213v1#bib.bib52" title=3D"AC/c++ code vulnerability dataset with code ch=
anges and cve summaries" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>)</cite> is used, as it =
provides CWE-type annotations necessary for input-space partitioning, as de=
scribed in Section <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#S3.SS2.SS=
S1" title=3D"3.2.1. Training Phase =E2=80=A3 3.2. Approach: MoEKD Framework=
 =E2=80=A3 3. Methodology =E2=80=A3 Leveraging Mixture of Experts (MoE) to =
Improve Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code" class=3D"ltx_re=
f"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">3.2.1</span></a>. BigVul comprises =
vulnerable and non-vulnerable functions collected from more than 300 open-s=
ource C and C++ projects, spanning 88 CWE types.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S4.SS2.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS2.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To address the severe class imbalance=
 in the original dataset, a balanced dataset is constructed using a structu=
red preprocessing pipeline. All vulnerable functions are retained, while no=
n-vulnerable functions are sampled in a project-stratified manner to preser=
ve project-specific context. To further control for confounding effects rel=
ated to function size, non-vulnerable samples are selected within a twenty =
percent range above or below the corresponding vulnerable function=E2=80=99=
s length, measured in lines of code. If no suitable match is available, a n=
on-vulnerable function is randomly selected from the same project. The resu=
lting dataset contains equal numbers of vulnerable and non-vulnerable funct=
ions and is randomly shuffled using a fixed seed to ensure reproducibility.=
 In accordance with prior studies <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cit=
ep">(Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib54" title=3D"One-for-all does not=
 work! enhancing vulnerability detection by mixture-of-experts (moe)" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite>, the dataset is divided into 80% for training=
, 10% for validation, and 10% for testing. Consistent with the standard sin=
gle-teacher knowledge distillation approach, the training split is further =
divided into two equal subsets: one for training the experts and router, an=
d the other for generating soft knowledge using a mixture of experts to tra=
in the student model. This preprocessing produces the final dataset used to=
 evaluate the <span id=3D"S4.SS2.p2.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic"=
>MoEKD</span> framework.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S4.SS2.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS2.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">CodeBERT <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_=
citemacro_citep">(Feng<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>,=
 <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib138" title=3D"Codebe=
rt: a pre-trained model for programming and natural languages" class=3D"ltx=
_ref">2020</a>)</cite> and GraphCodeBERT <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citema=
cro_citep">(Guo<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib140" title=3D"Graphcodebert=
: pre-training code representations with data flow" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020<=
/a>)</cite> serve as the underlying language models for code in this study.=
 CodeBERT is a pretrained Transformer-based model that adopts the architect=
ure of RoBERTa <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Liu, <a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib133" title=3D"Roberta: a rob=
ustly optimized bert pretraining approach" class=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>)</cit=
e>, comprising 12 Transformer layers with multi-head self-attention and a h=
idden dimensionality of 768. During pretraining, CodeBERT is optimized with=
 two objectives: masked language modeling, which learns contextual token re=
presentations by predicting masked tokens, and replaced token detection, wh=
ich distinguishes original tokens from substituted ones. The model is train=
ed on paired natural language and source code data from the CodeSearchNet c=
orpus <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Husain<span class=3D"lt=
x_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603=
.13213v1#bib.bib147" title=3D"Codesearchnet challenge: evaluating the state=
 of semantic code search" class=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>)</cite>, which include=
s six programming languages.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S4.SS2.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS2.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p">GraphCodeBERT extends CodeBERT by inc=
orporating structural information derived from program data-flow graphs. Wh=
ile maintaining the same Transformer architecture, GraphCodeBERT integrates=
 data-flow relationships between code tokens during pretraining and introdu=
ces an additional objective to predict the existence of data-flow edges bet=
ween nodes. This approach enables GraphCodeBERT to capture both semantic an=
d structural properties of source code more effectively than text-only repr=
esentations.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S4.SS3" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">4.3. </span>Evaluation Metrics</=
h3>

<div id=3D"S4.SS3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The effectiveness of the proposed <sp=
an id=3D"S4.SS3.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> fra=
mework is evaluated under two complementary settings: accuracy prior to adv=
ersarial attacks and robustness following adversarial attacks. This two-sta=
ge evaluation assesses whether <span id=3D"S4.SS3.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text=
 ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> improves both predictive performance and rob=
ustness relative to single-teacher distillation.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S4.SS3.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.1.1" class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_font_bold">Pre-attack performance</span>: Predictive performanc=
e under standard conditions is evaluated by measuring classification <span =
id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">accuracy</span> on =
the clean test set. Accuracy is the primary metric because the selected kno=
wledge distillation baselines consistently use it to compare student models=
 with their corresponding teacher models. This approach ensures a fair and =
direct comparison with prior work and enables assessment of whether mixture=
-of-experts-based distillation preserves or enhances the predictive perform=
ance of compact student models.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S4.SS3.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS3.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S4.SS3.p3.1.1" class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_font_bold">Post-attack robustness</span>: Robustness is assesse=
d by evaluating student models in adversarial settings using three state-of=
-the-art identifier renaming-based attack strategies: ALERT <cite class=3D"=
ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> e=
t al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib177" ti=
tle=3D"Natural attack for pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">202=
2</a>)</cite>, Metropolis Hastings Modifier (MHM) <cite class=3D"ltx_cite l=
tx_citemacro_citep">(Zhang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</sp=
an>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib176" title=3D"Ge=
nerating adversarial examples for holding robustness of source code process=
ing models" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>)</cite>, and WIR-Random <cite class=
=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Zeng<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal=
"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib378=
" title=3D"An extensive study on pre-trained models for program understandi=
ng and generation" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>)</cite>. ALERT applies greedy=
 and evolutionary search strategies over both operational and natural code =
semantics, using 30 candidate substitutions per identifier. MHM performs it=
erative identifier substitution via Metropolis=E2=80=93Hastings sampling, w=
ith a maximum of 100 iterations and 30 candidate evaluations per step. WIR-=
Random ranks identifiers according to their influence on model predictions =
and applies sequential random substitutions. These attacks maintain program=
 semantics while renaming identifiers to induce misclassification. Robustne=
ss is quantified using the Attack Success Rate (%ASR), which measures the p=
roportion of originally correctly classified samples that are misclassified=
 following the attack. A lower ASR reflects greater robustness. In all case=
s, adversarial attacks are applied only to samples that are correctly class=
ified prior to perturbation, as recommended by the previous research <cite =
class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib=
_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.b=
ib177" title=3D"Natural attack for pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx=
_ref">2022</a>; Zhang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, =
<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib176" title=3D"Generat=
ing adversarial examples for holding robustness of source code processing m=
odels" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>)</cite>.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S4.SS4" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">4.4. </span>Experimental Setting=
</h3>

<div id=3D"S4.SS4.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS4.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">All experiments were conducted on a L=
inux server running Ubuntu 22.04.5 LTS, equipped with an Intel Xeon Platinu=
m 8356H CPU, 3.0 TB RAM, and three NVIDIA A100 GPUs with 80 GB memory each.=
 Random seeds were fixed across all experiments to ensure reproducibility. =
CodeBERT was fine-tuned following the training pipeline and hyperparameter =
configurations defined in the CodeXGLUE benchmark <cite class=3D"ltx_cite l=
tx_citemacro_citep">(Lu<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>=
, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib377" title=3D"Codex=
glue: a machine learning benchmark dataset for code understanding and gener=
ation" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021</a>)</cite>, while GraphCodeBERT was trained =
using the hyperparameter settings reported in its original work <cite class=
=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Guo<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"=
> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib140"=
 title=3D"Graphcodebert: pre-training code representations with data flow" =
class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>)</cite>. CodeGraph and GraphCodeBERT were used a=
s the backbone of the experts and router model, similar to single-teacher d=
istillation, to mitigate experimental bias and ensure a fair comparison.</p=
>
</div>
<div id=3D"S4.SS4.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS4.p2.2" class=3D"ltx_p">The student models utilize compact ar=
chitectures generated by the baseline compression techniques <span id=3D"S4=
.SS4.p2.2.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> and <span=
 id=3D"S4.SS4.p2.2.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>. The=
 exact student architectures and training configurations identified by thes=
e baselines are reused without modification. This approach ensures that any=
 observed differences in predictive performance and adversarial robustness =
can be attributed exclusively to the proposed Mixture of Experts-based know=
ledge distillation strategy, rather than to architectural changes or robust=
ness-aware optimization. The architectural details of the compact student m=
odels are presented in Table <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1=
#S4.T1" title=3D"Table 1 =E2=80=A3 4.4. Experimental Setting =E2=80=A3 4. E=
mpirical Evaluation =E2=80=A3 Leveraging Mixture of Experts (MoE) to Improv=
e Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code" class=3D"ltx_ref"><sp=
an class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">1</span></a>. Since the number of selecte=
d experts plays a crucial role in effective knowledge aggregation and direc=
tly affects the trade-off between inference time and performance, we follow=
 the empirically validated top-<math id=3D"S4.SS4.p2.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Mat=
h" alttext=3D"k" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>k</m=
i><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">k</annotation></semantics></ma=
th> expert selection setting reported by Yang et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cit=
e ltx_citemacro_citep">(Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</=
span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib54" title=3D"O=
ne-for-all does not work! enhancing vulnerability detection by mixture-of-e=
xperts (moe)" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite>. Accordingly, we set <math=
 id=3D"S4.SS4.p2.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"k=3D2" display=3D"inli=
ne" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>2</mn></=
mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">k=3D2</annotation></semanti=
cs></math> for all experiments.</p>
</div>
