<section id=3D"S5" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">5. </span>Evaluation Results</h2>

<section id=3D"S5.SS1" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">5.1. </span><span id=3D"S5.SS1.2=
.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">RQ1: Pre-attack Performance</span>
</h3>

<div id=3D"S5.SS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Table <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/ht=
ml/2603.13213v1#S5.T2" title=3D"Table 2 =E2=80=A3 5.1. RQ1: Pre-attack Perf=
ormance =E2=80=A3 5. Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 Leveraging Mixture of Exp=
erts (MoE) to Improve Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code" c=
lass=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">2</span></a> presents=
 the classification accuracy of uncompressed teacher models and their corre=
sponding compressed student variants under standard (pre-attack) evaluation=
 settings. As expected, the uncompressed teacher models achieve the highest=
 accuracy, with CodeBERT and GraphCodeBERT attaining scores of 0.65 and 0.6=
4, respectively.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S5.SS1.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS1.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Model compression inevitably involves=
 trade-offs, as reducing the capacity of a code language model can degrade =
predictive performance, including lower accuracy on downstream tasks <cite =
class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_=
etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bi=
b7" title=3D"Compressing pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx=
_ref">2023</a>)</cite>. In particular, compressed student models obtained v=
ia single-teacher distillation exhibit a noticeable reduction in predictive=
 performance. For example, the <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p2.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text=
 ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span>-based student model achieves accuracies=
 of 0.54 (CodeBERT) and 0.59 (GraphCodeBERT), while the <span id=3D"S5.SS1.=
p2.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>-based student mode=
l attains 0.57 and 0.58, respectively. This degradation underscores the cha=
llenge of maintaining predictive performance when compressing language mode=
ls of code using conventional single-teacher supervision.</p>
</div>
