<div id=3D"S5.SS1.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS1.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">In contrast, student models trained u=
sing the proposed <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p3.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_ita=
lic">MoEKD</span> framework consistently outperform their single-teacher co=
unterparts across both backbone models. Specifically, the MoE-enhanced <spa=
n id=3D"S5.SS1.p3.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span>=
 student (MoE_CP) improves accuracy from 0.54 to 0.61 for CodeBERT, represe=
nting a relative improvement of approximately 13.7%, and from 0.59 to 0.62 =
for GraphCodeBERT, yielding an improvement of about 5.1%. Similarly, for <s=
pan id=3D"S5.SS1.p3.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>-b=
ased students, <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p3.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic=
">MoEKD</span> improves accuracy from 0.57 to 0.63 for CodeBERT, representi=
ng a relative gain of approximately 10.5%, and from 0.58 to 0.62 for GraphC=
odeBERT, corresponding to an improvement of about 6.9%. These results demon=
strate that distilling knowledge from a mixture of specialized experts yiel=
ds significantly stronger predictive performance than single-teacher distil=
lation, even under identical student architectures and training configurati=
ons.</p>
</div>
