<section id=3D"S5.SS2" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">5.2. </span><span id=3D"S5.SS2.2=
.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">RQ2: Post-attack Robustness</span>
</h3>

<div id=3D"S5.SS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Having established the predictive per=
formance gains achieved by compressed student models under the <span id=3D"=
S5.SS2.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> framework, w=
e now investigate its effectiveness in enhancing these models=E2=80=99 adve=
rsarial robustness relative to single-teacher distillation. Prior work by P=
anichella et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Panichella, =
<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib30" title=3D"Metamorp=
hic-based many-objective distillation of llms for code-related tasks" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite> has shown that knowledge-distilled student mo=
dels typically exhibit lower adversarial robustness than their teacher coun=
terparts; therefore, our robustness analysis compares <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p1=
.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>-distilled students wi=
th those trained using single-teacher distillation. Figure <a href=3D"https=
://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#S5.F4" title=3D"Figure 4 =E2=80=A3 5.2. RQ2:=
 Post-attack Robustness =E2=80=A3 5. Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 Leveragin=
g Mixture of Experts (MoE) to Improve Knowledge Distillation for Language M=
odels of Code" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">4</sp=
an></a> reports the Attack Success Rate (%ASR) under three adversarial atta=
cks for compressed models derived from both <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p1.1.3" clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> and <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p1.=
1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> architectures using C=
odeBERT and GraphCodeBERT backbones.</p>
</div>
