tag_figure">Figure 4. </span>Adversarial robustness comparison of single-te=
acher and <span id=3D"S5.F4.2.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</=
span>-based compressed student models across ALERT, MHM, and WIR-Random att=
acks, measured using the Attack Success Rate (ASR).</figcaption>
</figure>
<div id=3D"S5.SS2.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS2.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Since lower ASR indicates stronger ro=
bustness, across all evaluated settings, <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p2.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>-distilled student models consist=
ently exhibit improved adversarial robustness compared with their single-te=
acher distilled counterparts. For Compressor architecture-based students, m=
odels distilled with <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p2.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_=
italic">MoEKD</span> consistently achieve greater adversarial robustness th=
an those distilled with a single teacher across all three attack types. Thi=
s is shown by a consistent reduction in Attack Success Rate (%ASR) for both=
 CodeBERT and GraphCodeBERT backbones. Across ALERT, MHM, and WIR-Random at=
tacks, <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p2.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD<=
/span>-distilled Compressor students show robustness improvements of approx=
imately 8%=E2=80=9318% compared to single-teacher distillation, depending o=
n the attack and backbone model.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S5.SS2.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS2.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">A similar trend is observed among AVA=
TAR architecture-based students. <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p3.1.1" class=3D"ltx_te=
xt ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>-distilled AVATAR students achieve robustne=
ss improvements of up to 20%=E2=80=9330% compared to single-teacher counter=
parts across all attacks. These gains are consistent for both CodeBERT and =
GraphCodeBERT models, showing that <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p3.1.2" class=3D"ltx_=
text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>=E2=80=99s robustness benefits are not li=
mited to a specific architecture or compression method. These results indic=
ate that distilling knowledge from multiple specialized experts enables com=
pact student models to better learn decision boundaries and retain robustne=
ss relevant information that cannot be adequately transferred by a single t=
eacher, demonstrating the effectiveness of the <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p3.1.3" c=
lass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> framework.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S5.SS2.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS2.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To further determine whether the obse=
rved improvements in adversarial robustness are statistically significant, =
we conduct a paired statistical analysis comparing <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p4.1.=
1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>-distilled students with =
single-teacher counterparts across all attack settings. The Wilcoxon signed=
-rank <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Woolson, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib118" title=3D"Wilcoxon signed-rank =
test" class=3D"ltx_ref">2007</a>)</cite> test indicates that the robustness=
 improvements achieved by <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p4.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_=
font_italic">MoEKD</span> are statistically significant, with a p-value of =
0.006, suggesting that the observed gains are unlikely to be due to random =
variation. The corresponding Cliff=E2=80=99s delta value of <math id=3D"S5.=
SS2.p4.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\delta=3D0.618" display=3D"inlin=
e" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>0.61=
8</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\delta=3D0.618</ann=
otation></semantics></math> indicates a large effect size, confirming that =
the improvements are both statistically and practically significant. Overal=
l, these results provide strong empirical evidence that distilling knowledg=
e from multiple specialized experts significantly enhances the adversarial =
robustness of compressed student models compared to single-teacher distilla=
tion.</p>
</div>
