<div id=3D"S5.SS3.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS3.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S5.SS3.p3.1.1" class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_font_bold">Robustness under reduced model capacity: </span>
Table&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#S5.T4" title=3D"T=
able 4 =E2=80=A3 5.3. RQ3: Ablation Study on Knowledge Quality =E2=80=A3 5.=
 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 Leveraging Mixture of Experts (MoE) to Improv=
e Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code" class=3D"ltx_ref"><sp=
an class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">4</span></a> reports adversarial robustne=
ss as attack success rate (%ASR), where lower values indicate greater robus=
tness. MoE_CP generally outperforms the single-teacher baseline in most att=
ack scenarios. With aggressive compression, the &nbsp;1.6 MB MoE_CP model r=
educes ASR on ALERT from 0.62 to 0.59 and on Wir-Random from 0.72 to 0.70. =
For the MHM attack, the single-teacher baseline shows slightly better robus=
tness than the &nbsp;1.6 MB MoE_CP model (0.76 vs. 0.77). However, the &nbs=
p;2 MB MoE_CP model improves robustness across all three attacks, achieving=
 lower ASR than the baseline on ALERT (0.57 vs. 0.62), MHM (0.72 vs. 0.76),=
 and Wir-Random (0.69 vs. 0.72). Overall, these results provide empirical e=
vidence that distilling knowledge from multiple specialized experts yields =
higher-quality knowledge, which, when transferred to the student model, enh=
ances both the predictive accuracy and adversarial robustness of compressed=
 student models compared to single-teacher distillation.</p>
</div>
