<section id=3D"S6" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">6. </span>Discussion</h2>

<section id=3D"S6.SS1" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">6.1. </span>Inference Cost and T=
raining Overhead</h3>

<div id=3D"S6.SS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S6.SS1.p1.2" class=3D"ltx_p">When adopting <span id=3D"S6.SS1.p1.2=
.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span>, it is important to con=
sider the increased computational overhead during training. <span id=3D"S6.=
SS1.p1.2.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> uses multiple s=
pecialized expert models and a router, which increases training costs (e.g.=
, inference latency, energy consumption, and carbon footprint) compared to =
single-teacher distillation. In our case, this overhead scales with the num=
ber of experts, leading to a roughly tenfold increase in teacher-side compu=
tation during distillation. We recognize this cost as a trade-off for gaini=
ng richer and more diverse supervisory knowledge. This overhead is limited =
to the offline training phase. Furthermore, <span id=3D"S6.SS1.p1.2.3" clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> incurs additional computational=
 overhead during knowledge extraction. In contrast to single-teacher distil=
lation, which queries only one teacher model, <span id=3D"S6.SS1.p1.2.4" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> processes each input through =
the router and the top-<math id=3D"S6.SS1.p1.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" altte=
xt=3D"k" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>k</mi><annot=
ation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">k</annotation></semantics></math> sele=
cted experts (with <math id=3D"S6.SS1.p1.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=
=3D"k=3D2" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</m=
i><mo>=3D</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">k=
=3D2</annotation></semantics></math> in this study) to generate aggregated =
knowledge. Although this approach increases teacher-side computation during=
 distillation, the overhead is limited to the offline training phase and do=
es not impact inference-time efficiency. At inference, <span id=3D"S6.SS1.p=
1.2.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> employs the same com=
pact student architecture as baseline models, resulting in identical runtim=
e cost, memory usage, and latency. By improving predictive performance and =
adversarial robustness without increasing inference cost, <span id=3D"S6.SS=
1.p1.2.6" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> offers a favorabl=
e trade-off that prioritizes deployment efficiency and robustness, at the e=
xpense of higher one-time offline training cost.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S6.SS2" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">6.2. </span>Router Limitations a=
nd Potential Future Direction</h3>

<div id=3D"S6.SS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S6.SS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The proposed <span id=3D"S6.SS2.p1.1.=
1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> framework uses a vanilla=
 Mixture of Experts approach proposed by Jacobs et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_c=
ite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Jacobs<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et a=
l.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib59" title=
=3D"Adaptive mixtures of local experts" class=3D"ltx_ref">1991</a>)</cite>,=
 where knowledge extraction depends on effective input partitioning and app=
ropriate expert selection. The router model controls both factors, making i=
ts performance critical to the framework=E2=80=99s success. In our experime=
nts, the trained router achieved about <span id=3D"S6.SS2.p1.1.2" class=3D"=
ltx_text ltx_font_bold">&nbsp;62%</span> accuracy, meaning many vulnerable =
code instances were not routed to the most suitable experts. While <span id=
=3D"S6.SS2.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> demonstr=
ates measurable gains in performance and robustness compared to the baselin=
es, there remains significant room for further improvement. In addition, <s=
pan id=3D"S6.SS2.p1.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> cu=
rrently relies on a basic Mixture of Experts formulation, and incorporating=
 more advanced MoE architectures <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite=
p">(Fedus<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib61" title=3D"Switch transformers:=
 scaling to trillion parameter models with simple and efficient sparsity" c=
lass=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>; Lepikhin<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> e=
t al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib60" tit=
le=3D"Gshard: scaling giant models with conditional computation and automat=
ic sharding" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>)</cite> may further improve expert =
knowledge aggregation and enable more effective knowledge distillation.</p>
</div>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"S7" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">7. </span>Threats to Validity</h2>

<section id=3D"S7.SS1" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">7.1. </span>Internal Validity</h=
3>

<div id=3D"S7.SS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S7.SS1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">A primary threat to internal validity=
 arises when observed performance differences between teacher and student m=
odels stem from inconsistencies in training procedures, fine-tuning strateg=
ies, or data-processing choices, rather than from the knowledge distillatio=
n methods under evaluation. To address this risk, consistent training proto=
cols and uniform hyperparameter configurations were applied to all teacher =
and student models, in accordance with the settings reported in prior disti=
llation studies <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Shi<span clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/ht=
ml/2603.13213v1#bib.bib7" title=3D"Compressing pre-trained models of code i=
nto 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/260=
3.13213v1#bib.bib9" title=3D"Greening large language models of code" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2024a</a>; Panichella, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.=
13213v1#bib.bib30" title=3D"Metamorphic-based many-objective distillation o=
f llms for code-related tasks" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite>. Identica=
l data partitions were also used for fine-tuning and evaluation to ensure f=
air and controlled comparisons across all experimental conditions. Addition=
ally, experimental outcomes may be affected by implementation errors in the=
 training pipelines for both teacher and student models. To mitigate this t=
hreat, standardized training procedures from the <span id=3D"S7.SS1.p1.1.1"=
 class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">CodeXGLUE</span> benchmark were used fo=
r teacher-model fine-tuning and evaluation. For knowledge distillation base=
lines, student models for the BigVul dataset were reproduced using the offi=
cial replication packages provided by the authors of <span id=3D"S7.SS1.p1.=
1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor<span id=3D"footnote2" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">2</sup><spa=
n class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=3D"l=
tx_note_mark">2</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note"><span id=3D"footn=
ote2.1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_upright">2</span></span><span id=3D"=
footnote2.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_upright">https://github.com/soarsmu=
/Compressor</span></span></span></span></span>
and <span id=3D"S7.SS1.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR<sp=
an id=3D"footnote3" class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote"><sup class=3D"ltx_=
note_mark">3</sup><span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_co=
ntent"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">3</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_n=
ote"><span id=3D"footnote3.1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_upright">3</sp=
an></span><span id=3D"footnote3.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_upright">http=
s://github.com/soarsmu/Avatar</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S7.SS2" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">7.2. </span>Construct Validity</=
h3>

<div id=3D"S7.SS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S7.SS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">This study hypothesizes that aggregat=
ing knowledge from multiple expert models using a Mixture of Experts (MoE) =
mechanism enables more effective knowledge transfer during distillation tha=
n relying on a single teacher model. However, this hypothesis may not accou=
nt for all the variables that affect distillation outcomes. The analysis is=
 limited to sparse MoE configurations, whereas alternative MoE architecture=
s or routing strategies could facilitate more comprehensive knowledge aggre=
gation and potentially yield superior student models. Additionally, observe=
d improvements in performance may stem from architectural diversity or ense=
mble effects rather than from enhanced knowledge transfer alone. To mitigat=
e these potential confounding factors, the proposed method is evaluated aga=
inst established single-teacher distillation baselines under identical trai=
ning and evaluation protocols. Future research should systematically invest=
igate the impact of various expert aggregation strategies on the effectiven=
ess of knowledge distillation. The selection of adversarial attacks represe=
nts a potential limitation in construct validity, as the chosen classical a=
ttacks do not capture the full range of adversarial strategies relevant to =
compressed models. However, these attacks were selected for their capacity =
to introduce minimal perturbations while effectively deceiving compressed m=
odels in the experimental setting. Consequently, if compressed models exhib=
it limited robustness under these classical attack scenarios, they are like=
ly to be even more susceptible to advanced adversarial techniques.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S7.SS3" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">7.3. </span>External Validity</h=
3>

<div id=3D"S7.SS3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S7.SS3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Threats to external validity concern =
the extent to which the findings of this study can be generalized beyond th=
e specific models and tasks considered. The evaluation is conducted on the =
BigVul dataset using CodeBERT and GraphCodeBERT, both widely adopted for vu=
lnerability detection. Although the results may not directly generalize to =
other datasets or model architectures, the proposed approach is model-agnos=
tic and applicable to a broad range of code language models. Future researc=
h should examine the approach=E2=80=99s applicability across additional dat=
asets, programming languages, and model architectures to further assess its=
 generalizability. To facilitate reproducibility and future research, compr=
ehensive documentation of the methodology and experimental setup is provide=
d, and all code and scripts used in the experiments are publicly released.<=
/p>
</div>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"S8" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">8. </span>Related Work</h2>

<div id=3D"S8.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S8.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Model compression has been widely investi=
gated in computer vision and natural language processing as a means to redu=
ce the computational cost, memory footprint, and energy consumption of larg=
e language models <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Xu and McAu=
