/a>; Tang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib90" title=3D"Distilling task-spec=
ific knowledge from bert into simple neural networks" class=3D"ltx_ref">201=
9</a>)</cite>. Commonly adopted model compression techniques include prunin=
g <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Sanh<span class=3D"ltx_text=
 ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213=
v1#bib.bib41" title=3D"Movement pruning: adaptive sparsity by fine-tuning" =
class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>)</cite>, quantization <cite class=3D"ltx_cite lt=
x_citemacro_citep">(Zafrir<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</sp=
an>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib40" title=3D"Q8b=
ert: quantized 8bit bert" class=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>)</cite>, and knowledge=
 distillation <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Hinton<span cla=
ss=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/h=
tml/2603.13213v1#bib.bib42" title=3D"Distilling the knowledge in a neural n=
etwork" class=3D"ltx_ref">2015</a>)</cite>. Recently, these techniques have=
 been adapted to software analytics to improve the efficiency of code langu=
age models while maintaining acceptable performance <cite class=3D"ltx_cite=
 ltx_citemacro_citep">(Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</sp=
an>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib11" title=3D"Eff=
icient and green large language models for software engineering: vision and=
 the road ahead" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024b</a>)</cite>. Wei et al. <cite clas=
s=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Wei<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal=
"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib17"=
 title=3D"Towards greener yet powerful code generation via quantization: an=
 empirical study" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>)</cite> examined the effects o=
f quantization on code generation models and showed that, when applied appr=
opriately, it can substantially reduce resource usage with only minor impac=
ts on accuracy and robustness. Afrin et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_cit=
emacro_citep">(Afrin<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <=
a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib33" title=3D"Is quanti=
zation a deal-breaker? empirical insights from large code models" class=3D"=
ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite> investigated the effects of quantization beyond f=
unctional correctness, focusing on qualitative and static properties of gen=
erated code.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S8.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S8.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Subsequent work has further explored comp=
ression methods tailored to language models of code. Saad et al. <cite clas=
s=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Saad<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_eta=
l"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib19=
" title=3D"ALPINE: an adaptive language-agnostic pruning method for languag=
e models for code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>)</cite> proposed <span id=3D"=
S8.p2.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">ALPINE</span>, a language agn=
ostic pruning approach that reduces computational cost, while Aloisio et al=
. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(d=E2=80=99Aloisio<span clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/ht=
ml/2603.13213v1#bib.bib21" title=3D"On the compression of language models f=
or code: an empirical study on codebert" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>)</cite>=
 empirically compared pruning, quantization, and knowledge distillation for=
 CodeBERT across code summarization, vulnerability detection, and code sear=
ch tasks. Zhang et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Zhang<=
span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arx=
iv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib25" title=3D"Diet code is healthy: simplify=
ing programs for pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>)</c=
ite> showed that streamlining input programs for CodeBERT improves efficien=
cy with minimal impact on performance. While pruning and quantization impro=
ve efficiency, their compression capacity is limited, as aggressive compres=
sion often leads to performance degradation <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_cit=
emacro_citep">(Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a =
href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib7" title=3D"Compressing =
pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>)</cite>. C=
onsequently, this study focuses on knowledge distillation to obtain compact=
 models while preserving predictive performance.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S8.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S8.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Shi et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_ci=
temacro_citep">(Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a=
 href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib7" title=3D"Compressing=
 pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>)</cite> p=
roposed <span id=3D"S8.p3.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compresso=
r</span>, a knowledge distillation approach evaluated on CodeBERT and Graph=
CodeBERT for vulnerability prediction and clone detection, showing that mod=
el size and inference cost can be substantially reduced while preserving pr=
edictive performance. Building on this work, Shi et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_=
cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.=
</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib9" title=3D"=
Greening large language models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024a</a>)</cite>=
 introduced <span id=3D"S8.p3.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATA=
R</span>, which targets reductions in energy consumption and inference late=
ncy without sacrificing effectiveness. More recent studies have explored ro=
bustness-oriented and adaptive distillation strategies for code models. Pan=
ichella et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Panichella, <a=
 href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib30" title=3D"Metamorphi=
c-based many-objective distillation of llms for code-related tasks" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite> presented <span id=3D"S8.p3.1.3" class=3D"ltx=
_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span>, which integrates metamorphic testing w=
ith many objective optimization to improve robustness on metamorphic code w=
hile jointly optimizing accuracy, efficiency, and model size. Experiments o=
n CodeBERT and GraphCodeBERT show that MORPH achieves higher robustness and=
 efficiency than AVATAR without increasing model size. Liu et al. <cite cla=
ss=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Liu<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_eta=
l"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib32=
" title=3D"PIONEER: improving the robustness of student models when compres=
sing pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2026</a>)</cite> propose=
d <span id=3D"S8.p3.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">PIONEER</span>,=
 which enhances the robustness of compressed code models with minimal accur=
acy loss across multiple architectures. Chen et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite=
 ltx_citemacro_citep">(Chen<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</s=
pan>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib114" title=3D"S=
maller but better: self-paced knowledge distillation for lightweight yet ef=
fective lcms" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite> introduced <span id=3D"S8.=
p3.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">SODA</span>, a self-paced distil=
lation framework that progressively transfers programming knowledge and out=
performs prior distillation methods. Complementing these efforts, Wang et a=
l. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_citep">(Wang<span class=3D"ltx_tex=
t ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.1321=
3v1#bib.bib31" title=3D"An empirical study of knowledge distillation for co=
de understanding tasks" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite> provided an empi=
rical study showing that knowledge distillation consistently outperforms fi=
netuning for code understanding tasks, with feature-based approaches achiev=
ing the strongest performance.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S8.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S8.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p">In contrast to existing approaches that p=
rimarily optimize efficiency, robustness, or energy consumption in isolatio=
n, recent findings by Awal et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cit=
ep">(Awal<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://arxiv.org/html/2603.13213v1#bib.bib6" title=3D"A metamorphic testing=
 perspective on knowledge distillation for language models of code: does th=
e student deeply mimic the teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>)</cite> dem=
onstrate that even robustness-oriented knowledge distillation methods such =
as MORPH remain vulnerable to adversarial attacks, with student models exhi=
biting substantially lower robustness than their teacher counterparts. Thes=
e findings reveal a persistent gap in effectively transferring decision-lev=
el knowledge from teacher to student models, limiting students=E2=80=99 abi=
lity to faithfully capture the teacher=E2=80=99s decision boundaries. To ad=
dress this gap, our study integrates a Mixture of Experts strategy into the=
 knowledge distillation process to enable richer knowledge transfer and pro=
duce student models that achieve strong predictive performance and improved=
 adversarial robustness.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S9" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">9. </span>Conclusion</h2>

<div id=3D"S9.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S9.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">This study introduces the <span id=3D"S9.=
p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> framework, which en=
hances both predictive performance and adversarial robustness in compressed=
 language models of code, thereby improving their usability and reliability=
. <span id=3D"S9.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEKD</span> fo=
rmulates knowledge distillation as a teacher=E2=80=93student learning parad=
igm, drawing inspiration from higher education, and applies a Mixture of Ex=
perts framework to address this challenge. Our approach prioritizes knowled=
ge quality as a key factor in enhancing the performance of compressed stude=
nt models. When evaluated on CodeBERT and GraphCodeBERT models for the vuln=
erability detection task, <span id=3D"S9.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font=
_italic">MoEKD</span> increases predictive performance by up to 13% and adv=
ersarial robustness by up to 30% compared to <span id=3D"S9.p1.1.4" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> and <span id=3D"S9.p1.1.5" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>. Our ablation study confir=
ms the importance of high-quality aggregated knowledge extracted from a spe=
cialized mixture of experts in improving the overall performance and robust=
ness of language models of code. In future work, we will assess the general=
izability of <span id=3D"S9.p1.1.6" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MoEK=
D</span> across additional models and software engineering tasks, and explo=
re advanced MoE architectures to further enhance expert knowledge aggregati=
on and enable more effective knowledge distillation.</p>
</div>
</section>
